Edited the "Real-time file Scanning" field - because apparently people here just care about lobbying to promote proprietary software... And didn't do nothing during that time to update  this field (that wasn't updated for YEARS).

Regarding Splunk's study, there was't important information about its reliability while scanning certain kinds of files & malware - took advantage of the work made by previous volunteers that I found in the reviewing history, and did adapt the text. NOTE: "Trojans" aren't necessarily the same as "Banking Trojans", so be careful about those terminology changes.
There  was some weird punctuation, example: "programs designed to steal client information. E.g. Keyloggers". Added some " - ".

The last statement "while critiquing it for being somewhat difficult to use" was very vague, and wasn't explaining very important facts for the readers can understand why it was classified was "difficult to use". Added important information to justify it.
Lack of attention regarding punctuation - added a period.
There was a grammar mistake made by the previous editors.
Spotted a grammar mistake commited by my end
I saw some issues around the latest editions - so I decided to input some recent data from an article's review (from a relatively popular cybersecurity website).
Changed the title for one more suitable
Tried to add more info to the description
Updated data about the current number of users - data obtained from Skiff's official twitter posts.
Changes in the description, because it didn't have a lot of info and was super short.
Added some "News References" - will add more for this field over time
Put results after description of study, not before.
